    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down. | Beckenham. Kent.</placeName>
                    <date>Ap<hi rend="superscript">l</hi>. 8. 1872.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Professor Donders,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am greatly obliged to you for having taken such great trouble to illuminate one as ignorant as I am on the functions of the eye—<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Your information has been many times of the greatest use to me; &amp; what is even a still greater kindness, you have saved me from having fallen into many errors—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I have received the German Pamphlet &amp; read the part indicated; &amp; have written to Bowman to borrow M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Wells’ work.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> When I go again over my M.S., I will carefully reconsider all that I have written; &amp; as the subject is so intricate, the result I think will be that I will strike out a good deal, &amp; only give some facts &amp; quote what you have told me—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I feel every day that to write on expression, a man ought to have ten times as much physiological knowledge as I possess; but I hope to succeed in giving a good many observations, especially on the expression and gestures of Savages; &amp; then some one hereafter will correct my speculations.</p>
<p>I must again say how extremely kind it is in you, full of knowledge &amp; busily employed as you are to spend so much time in aiding me.</p>
<p>Believe me | Yours very gratefully— | Charles Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

